# Chapter 4 — Percussion

A percussion instrument is one whose sound is defined by an attack
and a decay, with no sustained middle. You hit it, it rings for a
moment, it fades. Everything else about percussion — whether it has
a pitch, how long it takes to decay, whether it can be rolled, how
it colors a rhythm — is a variation on the shape of that attack and
that decay.

This chapter is about attacks, decays, and the split between **tuned
percussion** (marimba, vibraphone, timpani — instruments that
produce a definite pitch) and **untuned percussion** (snare, kick,
cymbal — instruments that produce a noise-like sound with no clear
pitch). Both families use the same primitives: hit it, hear it,
schedule the next hit.

*Percussion is where the piece keeps time. A melody wanders. A
chord blooms. A percussion hit lands. Without percussion the ear
has no metronome except the composer's intention. With percussion
the pulse is felt, not measured. That is why almost every genre
of music on earth has some form of percussion — the ear needs a
beat to hang the rest of the sound on.*

## 4.1 One hit — the smallest percussion program

A single kick drum hit. No sustain, no articulation, just impact and
decay.

```scheme
(begin
  (synth/select 'kick)
  (play/note 'kick 'sixteenth))
```

You hear one thump. The onset is nearly instantaneous — the strike
of the beater on the drumhead. The decay is fast — a fraction of a
second. That is the entire percussion event. Notice that the pitch
symbol is `'kick` rather than a note name like `'c4`; untuned
percussion does not have a definite pitch, so the engine takes the
kind-name as the \"note.\"

## 4.2 A pattern — kick, snare, kick, snare

The essential rock beat. Four hits, alternating kick and snare, on
each quarter beat.

```scheme
(begin
  (tempo 120)
  (in-order
    (begin (synth/select 'kick) (play/note 'kick 'quarter))
    (begin (synth/select 'snare) (play/note 'snare 'quarter))
    (begin (synth/select 'kick) (play/note 'kick 'quarter))
    (begin (synth/select 'snare) (play/note 'snare 'quarter))))
```

You hear the four hits: thump-crack-thump-crack. This is the atomic
form of every backbeat you have ever heard. Change the tempo and you
change the genre — 60 for a slow ballad, 120 for a rock song, 180
for a fast punk feel. The pattern does not change; the tempo does.

## 4.3 A hi-hat pulse — the ride pattern

Underneath the kick-and-snare there is usually a faster, quieter
pulse — a hi-hat or ride cymbal ticking away at eighth or sixteenth
notes. Here is a sixteenth-note hi-hat pattern.

```scheme
(begin
  (tempo 100)
  (synth/select 'hi-hat)
  (play/dynamics! 'p)
  (in-order
    (play/note 'hi-hat 'sixteenth)
    (play/note 'hi-hat 'sixteenth)
    (play/note 'hi-hat 'sixteenth)
    (play/note 'hi-hat 'sixteenth)
    (play/note 'hi-hat 'sixteenth)
    (play/note 'hi-hat 'sixteenth)
    (play/note 'hi-hat 'sixteenth)
    (play/note 'hi-hat 'sixteenth)))
```

Eight quick, quiet ticks — the \"chick-chick-chick\" of a hi-hat.
Notice the `play/dynamics! 'p` — hi-hats should not compete with
the kick and snare for attention. They set the pulse; they do not
carry the rhythm.

## 4.4 A tuned percussion instrument — marimba

Marimba is percussion that plays notes. You hit a wooden bar and it
rings at a specific pitch. The decay is longer than a kick drum's,
and the pitch is definite — you can play melodies on it.

```scheme
(begin
  (synth/select 'marimba)
  (in-order
    (play/note 'c4 'eighth)
    (play/note 'e4 'eighth)
    (play/note 'g4 'eighth)
    (play/note 'c5 'quarter)))
```

You hear a rising C-major arpeggio — hollow, wooden, with each note
ringing for about a beat before fading. Marimba is what \"wooden
xylophone\" sounds like at a larger, more resonant scale. It is
tuned percussion at its most singable.

## 4.5 A roll — sustaining an unsustainable instrument

Percussion does not sustain, but if you hit it fast enough, it
sounds sustained. A drum roll is a rapid sequence of hits that the
ear reads as a continuous sound. `play/roll` schedules a roll at a
given rate for a given duration.

```scheme
(begin
  (synth/select 'snare)
  (play/dynamics! 'mf)
  (play/roll 'snare 'sixteenth 'whole))
```

A whole-note snare roll made of sixteenth-note hits. The individual
hits are fast enough that the ear does not resolve them — it hears
a sustained \"shhhhhh\" of snare. This is how you cross the fundamental
limit of percussion: you cannot sustain a hit, so you sustain a
sequence.

## 4.6 A cymbal crash — long decay, no pitch

The cymbal is the percussion instrument with the longest decay. A
struck ride or crash rings for seconds before it fades. `synth/damp!`
is the verb that cuts it off early if you want it to stop before its
natural decay.

```scheme
(begin
  (synth/select 'crash)
  (play/note 'crash 'sixteenth)
  ;; ring for a full beat
  (rest 'whole)
  ;; cut it off
  (synth/damp! 'crash)
  (rest 'quarter))
```

You hear the crash strike, ring for a beat, then get cut off by the
damper. Cymbal damping is what a drummer does with a hand on the
edge of the cymbal after a big hit — stop the ring before it
smears into the next phrase.

## 4.7 A tuned + untuned combination

The real power of percussion is combining tuned and untuned in the
same passage. Marimba plays a melodic figure; kick and snare and
hi-hat provide the pulse underneath.

```scheme
(begin
  (tempo 100)
  (together
    (in-order
      (synth/select 'marimba)
      (play/note 'c4 'eighth)
      (play/note 'e4 'eighth)
      (play/note 'g4 'eighth)
      (play/note 'e4 'eighth)
      (play/note 'c4 'eighth)
      (play/note 'e4 'eighth)
      (play/note 'g4 'eighth)
      (play/note 'c5 'quarter))
    (in-order
      (synth/select 'kick) (play/note 'kick 'quarter)
      (synth/select 'snare) (play/note 'snare 'quarter)
      (synth/select 'kick) (play/note 'kick 'quarter)
      (synth/select 'snare) (play/note 'snare 'quarter))
    (in-order
      (synth/select 'hi-hat)
      (play/dynamics! 'p)
      (play/note 'hi-hat 'eighth)
      (play/note 'hi-hat 'eighth)
      (play/note 'hi-hat 'eighth)
      (play/note 'hi-hat 'eighth)
      (play/note 'hi-hat 'eighth)
      (play/note 'hi-hat 'eighth)
      (play/note 'hi-hat 'eighth)
      (play/note 'hi-hat 'eighth))))
```

Three simultaneous lines. Marimba plays a melodic figure on top.
Kick and snare set the backbeat. Hi-hat ticks the eighth-note
pulse. This is the shape of a small groove — three percussion
voices that fit together because they occupy different roles
(melody, backbeat, subdivision) rather than different pitches.

*A common mistake is to think of percussion as one thing. It is
not. In any passage of music with percussion there are almost
always three roles: the pulse-keeper (usually hi-hat or shaker),
the backbeat (usually kick and snare), and — if there is one — a
tuned percussion line (marimba, vibes, timpani). Once you hear
those three roles, the whole family of drums becomes composable.
You are not writing \"drums.\" You are writing three little
functions that happen to be percussion.*

> **Under the hood**
>
> Tuned-percussion profiles (marimba, vibraphone, timpani) are
> physical models of struck bars or membranes with definite pitch.
> They compute a set of oscillator modes with characteristic decay
> times and mix them per note. Untuned-percussion profiles (kick,
> snare, cymbals) are noise-based: a filtered noise burst shaped by
> a fast-attack envelope, with the frequency profile tuned to
> emulate the specific instrument's frequency signature.
> `play/roll` is scheduling sugar: it expands to a sequence of
> hits at the given subdivision across the given duration.
> `synth/damp!` cuts an active note's decay envelope short.

## What you know now

- Percussion is attack + decay; no sustained middle.
- Untuned percussion (kick, snare, cymbal) uses a kind-name for
  the \"note.\"
- Tuned percussion (marimba, vibes, timpani) uses pitch names like
  a piano.
- `play/roll` fakes sustain by hitting fast enough that the ear
  cannot separate the hits.
- `synth/damp!` cuts a long decay short.
- The three percussion roles: pulse-keeper, backbeat, tuned
  melody. Write each as its own line.

Next chapter: **the Japanese bamboo flute** — an instrument whose
silences are half its voice.

